DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(91)90011-T
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/002219969190011T
AB  - This paper revisits the question of whether a sovereign's desire for future access to international credit markets, which it retains by paying its international debts, constitutes by itself enough of an incentive to make it a reliable customer for commercial lenders. The answer is no, as it is in the earlier analysis of Bulow and Rogoff, but the result here is in certaincases stronger: a defaulter here is excluded from participating in credit markets as both a debtor and a creditor, whereas in the previous analysis a key assumption was that defaulters could return as creditors.
